5 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
6 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
7 Article – State Personnel and Pensions
8 Section 1–101(a) and (b)
9 Annotated Code of Maryland
10 (2024 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
11 BY adding to
12 Article – State Personnel and Pensions
13 Section 2–206 and 2–207
14 Annotated Code of Maryland
15 (2024 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
16 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
17 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
18 Article – State Finance and Procurement
19 11–101.
20 (a) In this Division II the following words have the meanings indicated unless:
21 (1) the context clearly requires a different meaning; or
22 (2) a different definition is provided for a particular title or provision.
23 (d) “Board” means the Board of Public Works.
24 (aa) (1) “Unit” means an officer or other entity that is in the Executive Branch
25 of the State government and is authorized by law to enter into a procurement contract.
26 (2) “Unit” does not include:
27 (i) a bistate, multistate, bicounty, or multicounty governmental
28 agency; or
29 (ii) a special tax district, sanitary district, drainage district, soil
30 conservation district, water supply district, or other political subdivision of the State.
31 15–113.

SENATE BILL 859 3
1 (a) In this section, “liquidated damages” means damages in an amount
2 designated by the parties to a contract that the injured party is eligible to collect as
3 compensation for a specific breach of the contract.
4 (d) A unit shall obtain the approval of the head of the unit if the unit decides not
5 to include in a contract a liquidated damages clause specified under § 13–218(a)(4) of this
6 article.
7 (e) [(1) This subsection applies only to procurements valued at $5,000,000 or
8 more.
9 (2)] If a unit decides not to pursue liquidated damages when a specified
10 breach associated with a liquidated damages provision has occurred, the unit shall:
11 [(i)] (1) obtain the approval of the decision by the head of the unit;
12 [and]
13 [(ii)] (2) maintain documentation on the reason the unit decided
14 not to pursue liquidated damages; AND
15 (3) PROVIDE DOCUMENTATION TO THE BOARD AND THE JOINT
16 AUDIT AND EVALUATION COMMITTEE ON THE REASON THAT THE UNIT INTENDS
17 NOT TO PURSUE LIQUIDATED DAMAGES.
18 Article – State Personnel and Pensions
19 1–101.
20 (a) In this Division I of this article the following words have the meanings
21 indicated.
22 (b) “Appointing authority” means an individual or a unit of government that has
23 the power to make appointments and terminate employment.
24 2–206.
25 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER” INCLUDES MEANS:
26 (1) AN INDIVIDUAL ACTING AS CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER FOR A
27 PERIOD OF 3 MONTHS OR LONGER; AND
28 (2) A POSITION EQUIVALENT TO A CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER

4 SENATE BILL 859
1 (1) THE HIGHEST RANKING EXECUTIVE WHO, FOR A PERIOD OF AT
2 LEAST 6 MONTHS, IS RESPONSIBLE FOR DIRECTING ALL FINANCIAL OPERATIONS,
3 INCLUDING:
4 (I) BUDGETING;
5 (II) ACCOUNTING;
6 (III) PROCUREMENT;
7 (IV) GRANT MANAGEMENT;
8 (V) ESTABLISHING FISCAL POLICIES;
9 (VI) ENSURING COMPLIANCE WITH STATE AND FEDERAL
10 REGULATIONS; AND
11 (VII) PROVIDING STRATEGIC FINANCIAL LEADERSHIP TO
12 AGENCY LEADERSHIP; OR
13 (2) A POSITION WITH EQUIVALENT DUTIES.
14 (B) (1) THIS EXCEPT AS PROVIDED UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS
15 SUBSECTION, THIS SECTION APPLIES TO A UNIT OF THE EXECUTIVE BRANCH OF
16 STATE GOVERNMENT THAT:
17 (1) (I) RECEIVES AT LEAST $2,000,000,000 $1,750,000,000
18 ANNUALLY IN STATE AND FEDERAL FUNDING; AND
19 (2) (II) EMPLOYS A CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER.
20 (2) THIS SECTION DOES NOT APPLY TO THE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM OF
21 MARYLAND.
22 (C) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER PROVISION OF LAW, AT THE REQUEST
23 OF AN APPOINTING AUTHORITY, THE SECRETARY MAY GRANT AN EXEMPTION TO
24 THE STATE PAY PLAN TO ASSIST UNITS OF STATE GOVERNMENT IN THE
25 RECRUITMENT AND RETENTION OF CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICERS THE SECRETARY
26 MAY SET THE PAY SCALE FOR CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER POSITIONS IN ORDER TO
27 ASSIST WITH RECRUITMENT AND RETENTION.
28 (D) AN APPOINTING AUTHORITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION SHALL MAKE AN
29 APPOINTMENT OF A CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER WHO MEETS THE REQUIREMENTS
30 QUALIFICATIONS IN SUBSECTION (E) OF THIS SECTION.

SENATE BILL 859 5
1 (E) A CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER OF A UNIT OF STATE GOVERNMENT
2 SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION SHALL:
3 (1) (I) BE A CERTIFIED PUBLIC ACCOUNTANT WITH 5 YEARS OF
4 EXPERIENCE IN FISCAL MANAGEMENT IN THE PRIVATE OR PUBLIC SECTOR WITH A
5 MINIMUM OF 2 YEARS OF EXPERIENCE IN A HIGH–LEVEL MANAGEMENT POSITION;
6 OR
7 (II) POSSESS A MASTER’S DEGREE IN BUSINESS
8 ADMINISTRATION, FINANCE, OR A RELATED FIELD FROM AN ACCREDITED
9 INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION WITH 3 YEARS OF EXPERIENCE IN FISCAL
10 MANAGEMENT IN THE PRIVATE OR PUBLIC SECTOR WITH A MINIMUM OF 2 YEARS OF
11 EXPERIENCE IN A HIGH–LEVEL MANAGEMENT POSITION; OR
12 (2) HAVE A DOCUMENTED RECORD OF MANAGEMENT WITH AT LEAST
13 10 YEARS’ EXPERIENCE IN FISCAL MANAGEMENT IN THE PRIVATE OR PUBLIC
14 SECTOR, WITH A MINIMUM OF 5 YEARS OF EXPERIENCE IN A HIGH–LEVEL
15 MANAGEMENT POSITION.
16 (F) (1) A CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER OF A UNIT OF STATE GOVERNMENT
17 SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION SHALL PROVIDE TO THE OFFICE OF THE COMPTROLLER
18 FOR THE ANNUAL COMPREHENSIVE FINANCIAL REPORT, REQUIRED UNDER §
19 2–102 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE, ALL NECESSARY
20 ENTRIES OF THE UNIT’S FINANCIAL INFORMATION AT THE CLOSE OF THE FISCAL
21 YEAR.
22 (2) THE CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER THAT REPORTS TO THE
23 COMPTROLLER UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION SHALL:
24 (I) ENSURE THAT EACH ENTRY IN THE UNIT’S FINANCIAL
25 INFORMATION IS ADEQUATE AND ACCURATELY RECORDED; AND
26 (II) CERTIFY TO THE COMPTROLLER THE ADEQUACY AND
27 ACCURACY OF THE FINANCIAL INFORMATION WITH A STATEMENT THAT:
28 1. ALL FEDERAL FUND RECEIVABLES ARE PROPERLY
29 SUPPORTED AND CAN BE DIRECTLY ASSOCIATED WITH A SPECIFIC FEDERAL
30 FUNDING STREAM; AND
31 2. THE STATE CAN REASONABLY EXPECT TO RECEIVE
32 FUNDS WITHIN 60 DAYS FOR THE SUBSEQUENT FISCAL YEAR UNLESS SPECIFIC
33 FEDERAL LANGUAGE ALLOWS FOR A LONGER RECOVERY PERIOD.

6 SENATE BILL 859
1 (3) IN ADDITION TO THE REQUIREMENTS SPECIFIED IN PARAGRAPHS
2 (1) AND (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER SHALL PROVIDE
3 TO THE GENERAL ACCOUNTING DIVISION OF THE OFFICE OF THE COMPTROLLER:
4 (I) THE INFORMATION NECESSARY TO PREPARE THE ANNUAL
5 COMPREHENSIVE FINANCIAL REPORT AND SCHEDULE OF EXPENDITURES OF
6 FEDERAL AWARDS; AND
7 (II) A LETTER ATTESTING TO THE ACCURACY AND
8 COMPLETENESS OF THE INFORMATION PROVIDED UNDER ITEM (I) OF THIS
9 PARAGRAPH.
10 (E) (1) THE SECRETARY SHALL ESTABLISH MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS
11 FOR CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER POSITIONS THAT CONSIDER:
12 (I) EDUCATION;
13 (II) EXECUTIVE EXPERIENCE AND THE DURATION OF THAT
14 EXPERIENCE;
15 (III) SUPERVISORY OR MANAGERIAL EXPERIENCE;
16 (IV) TECHNICAL COMPETENCE;
17 (V) CERTIFICATIONS;
18 (VI) SCOPE AND COMPLEXITY OF THE ROLE; AND
19 (VII) ALIGNMENT WITH THE GOVERNMENT OR INDUSTRY
20 STANDARDS.
21 (2) ON OR BEFORE NOVEMBER 1, 2026, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL
22 ADOPT REGULATIONS TO ESTABLISH MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS FOR CHIEF
23 FINANCIAL OFFICER POSITIONS.
24 (F) FOR PREPARATION OF THE ANNUAL COMPREHENSIVE FINANCIAL
25 REPORT REQUIRED UNDER § 2–102 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT
26 ARTICLE, A CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER OF A UNIT OF STATE GOVERNMENT SUBJECT
27 TO THIS SECTION SHALL PROVIDE TO THE OFFICE OF THE COMPTROLLER AT THE
28 CLOSE OF THE FISCAL YEAR:
29 (1) ALL NECESSARY ENTRIES OF THE UNIT’S FINANCIAL
30 INFORMATION;

SENATE BILL 859 7
1 (2) THE INFORMATION NECESSARY TO PREPARE THE SCHEDULE OF
2 EXPENDITURES OF FEDERAL AWARDS IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE FEDERAL
3 LAWS AND REGULATIONS; AND
4 (3) A LETTER ATTESTING TO THE ACCURACY AND COMPLETENESS OF
5 THE INFORMATION PROVIDED IN ITEMS (1) AND (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
6 2–207.
7 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “CHIEF INFORMATION OFFICER” MEANS:
8 (1) AN INDIVIDUAL ACTING AS THE SENIOR EXECUTIVE OFFICER
9 RESPONSIBLE FOR THE STRATEGIC PLANNING, MANAGEMENT, AND OVERSIGHT OF
10 AN AGENCY’S INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY AND COMPUTER SYSTEMS AND
11 SUPPORTING ITS MISSION AND GOALS, INCLUDING THROUGH:
12 (I) PROCUREMENT;
13 (II) COMPLIANCE WITH STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS;
14 AND
15 (III) PROVIDING INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY LEADERSHIP TO
16 AGENCY LEADERSHIP; OR
17 (2) A POSITION WITH EQUIVALENT DUTIES.
18 (B) (1) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS
19 SUBSECTION, THIS SECTION APPLIES TO A UNIT OF THE EXECUTIVE BRANCH OF
20 STATE GOVERNMENT THAT EMPLOYS A CHIEF INFORMATION OFFICER.
21 (2) THIS SECTION DOES NOT APPLY TO THE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM OF
22 MARYLAND.
23 (C) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER PROVISION OF LAW, THE SECRETARY
24 MAY SET THE PAY SCALE FOR CHIEF INFORMATION OFFICER POSITIONS IN ORDER
25 TO ASSIST WITH RECRUITMENT AND RETENTION.
26 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
27 1, 2026.

